	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New EU proposal for a General System of Preferences: implications for ACP countries post-Cotonou</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> On October 20th 2004, the European Commission adopted a proposal that sets out the details for a new EU General System of Preferences (GSP). This will replace the current regulation that expired on December 31st 2004. The new proposal states that 'a key priority is to help developing countries to benefit from globalisation, in particular by linking trade and sustainable development'. For further details see the item in the main Agritrade News Update for November and the item on comments on the new scheme in the December Update.</p><p> Of the 240 new products covered, about two-thirds are fish or fishery products. The new regulation maintains the current flat-rate reduction of 3.5 percentage points for sensitive products, like fish and fishery products, and 100% for non-sensitive products.</p><p> A special provision has been introduced for fisheries under Title III, 'Temporary withdrawal and safeguard provisions'. Article 15 states that: 'The preferential arrangements provided for in this regulation may be temporarily withdrawn, in respect of all or of certain products, originating in a beneficiary country, for ? (f) serious and systematic infringements of the objectives of regional fishery organisations or arrangements to which the Community is a member concerning the conservation and management of fishery resources.'</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.cymru.gov.uk/keypubassemeuropeancomm2/content/euleg041025/13931-04.pdf" target="_self">Commission proposal for a council regulation applying a scheme of genera...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.tralac.org/scripts/content.php?id=3008" target="_self">tralac (Trade Law Centre for Southern Africa) news, October 25th 2004</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Despite the advantages of GSP+ for ACP countries, the Cotonou Agreement still provides more favourable terms of access. The important question therefore arises as to whether this new GSP proposal will provide adequate access arrangements for those ACP countries that do not enter EPAs with the EU after 2007. Under such circumstances, they might well see their preferential access to the EU market for fish eroded, and find themselves at a competitive disadvantage vis-à-vis other developing countries.</p><p> ACP countries also need to be aware of the implications of the 'Temporary withdrawal and safeguard provisions' (Title III, Article 15 of the GSP+ proposal). This foresees the withdrawal of the preferential arrangements, for all or certain products, for 'serious and systematic infringements of the objectives of regional fishery organisations or arrangements to which the Community is a member concerning the conservation and management of fishery resources'.</p><p> Whilst any efforts to ensure compliance with the objectives of regional fisheries organisations (RFOs) should be welcomed, it seems that in this case the EU is adopting a 'carrot and stick' approach, but without any carrot. Many ACP countries still lack sufficient capacity for the fisheries research, monitoring, surveillance and control, etc needed to allow full participation in RFOs, and to enable them to effectively comply with the objectives of RFOs. Specific programmes therefore need to be designed, supported by external financing, otherwise ACP countries will find it virtually impossible to comply with RFO objectives, and hence to benefit from the new GSP+ arrangements.</p><p> At the same time, several additional issues are likely to play an increasingly important role in defining the levels of access that ACP fishery products will enjoy on the EU market. These include the various new EU standards (phytosanitary standards, and standards on maximum residue levels, traceability, etc). For many ACP countries, overcoming such non-tariff barriers will also require significant external financial and technical assistance.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
